<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Hamburg voters snub establishment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE VOTERS of Hamburg last night delivered a resounding snub to the ruling
coalition of Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and to the opposition Social Democrats,
in a clear indication of popular anger with the German political
establishment.
The winners in the city election campaign were all the protest parties, led
by the Greens, who almost doubled their support from 7.1 per cent in the
last election to 13.5 per cent last night.
A non-political citizens' protest party, called the Statt (Instead) Partei,
won eight seats in the 121-member Hamburg parliament with a vote of 5.7 per
cent.
To universal relief, the extreme right-wing Republicans failed to win any
seats by the narrowest of margins, gaining 4.9 per cent support - just below
the 5.0 per cent needed to enter the assembly.
Both Mr Kohl's Christian Democratic Union, with a slump from 35 to 25 per
cent support in the election, and the SPD suffered their worst poll results
in the city since the second world war.
The setback to the ruling establishment was confirmed by a disastrous result
for the liberal Free Democratic party, the minority partner in Mr Kohl's
Bonn coalition, which will lose all its seats in the parliament. Its support
tumbled from 5.4 to 4.1 per cent.
The Hamburg city election, called two years early after the CDU was found
guilty of undemocratic methods of selecting its party candidates in 1991, is
the first of no fewer than 20 national, state and local elections in the
next 13 months.
The SPD, which has ruled Hamburg virtually without interruption for 46
years, ended the night with 40.4 per cent support, compared with 48 per cent
in 1991, giving it 58 seats in the parliament. It has therefore lost its
absolute majority of one seat, and will now have to negotiate - either with
the CDU, the Greens, or the Statt party - to form a coalition city
government.
The collapse in the CDU vote was the biggest surprise of the night. Mr
Kohl's party was clearly one of the main losers to the Statt party, which
was formed by dissident Christian Democrats. The FDP also lost support to
the non-party protesters.
The result for the Republicans was clearly a disappointment for the party,
which had been slipping in recent opinion polls. However, the total
far-right vote, including the German People's Union (DVU), reached almost 10
per cent. The result for the extremists suggests their overall support has
peaked.
Mr Henning Voscherau, the Hamburg lord mayor and SPD party leader in
Hamburg, must now decide with whom to negotiate a coalition city government.
The most likely outcome is a coalition with the Greens, who campaigned
openly in favour of such an outcome.
</TEXT>
