<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / German Free Democrats criticise Steffan Heitmann for
Holocaust remarks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Steffen Heitmann, Chancellor Helmut Kohl's candidate for federal
president when the post is vacated in May, yesterday came under criticism
from the Free Democrats, the junior partner in the governing coalition, for
remarks he made about the Holocaust, writes Judy Dempsey in Berlin.
In an interview with the Suddeutsche Zeitung daily, Mr Heitmann, justice
minister of the eastern state of Saxony, said: 'The time has come - now that
the post-war period is finally over after German unification - to put this
event (the Nazi period) in its proper place.' He said the killing of 6m Jews
by the Nazis was a unique event, but that Germany 'must not have a special
role until the end of time'.
Mr Hermann Otto Solms, parliamentary leader of the Free Democrats, told the
Bild am Sonntag newspaper that Mr Heitmann's comments 'make me doubt if he
has really understood the people of our country and German history'.
Mr Heitmann's remarks on the Holocaust follow last week's controversial
comments challenging ratification of the Maastricht treaty. In an interview
with El Pais, the Spanish daily newspaper, Mr Heitmann was reported to have
said the Maastricht treaty had been 'imposed' on European Community
countries.
'It was not a result of a big debate over European unification, but it was
ordered from above.'
The Christian Social Union, sister party of Mr Kohl's Christian Democratic
Union, still has to decide whether to back the CDU's candidate. But the
controversy surrounding Mr Heitmann may persuade the Free Democrats to apply
more pressure on Mr Hans Dietrich Genscher, the former foreign minister, to
stand, despite his reluctance.
</TEXT>
