<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Major set for showdown with rebels: PM urges his rightwing
critics to stop the squabbling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, TORQUAY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR, the prime minister, yesterday admitted that rightwing critics
of his leadership were undermining the government's authority.
Mr Major's startlingly frank call for party unity, to allow the government
to function normally, confirmed that the future of his leadership would be
the dominant theme of the autumn party conference season.
It sets the scene for a showdown with the rightwing rebels at next month's
party conference which will be a crucial test of Mr Major's leadership.
Speaking in Tokyo, where he is on a four-day official visit, Mr Major left
no doubt that his patience with the rebels had run out: 'It is time to cut
out this stupid internecine squabbling and get on with the job the country
elected us to do. That is their job, as well as mine.'
Mr Major's decision to tackle his critics confirms that their persistent
sniping is beginning to wear him down, despite official attempts to belittle
them.
Mr Major warned the rebels that the leadership controversy had to end to
allow his government to work properly: 'When decisions need to be taken, and
those decisions are in the interests of the British people, then I have the
right to ask for the support of parliament, particularly the support of my
party. That is what I intend to do.'
Mr Major plans a showdown with the right at the Conservative party
conference in Blackpool which he believes he will win easily. He said: 'The
Conservative party in the country is sick and tired of these distractions,
and I think they will show that at the conference.'
The television interviews were intended as the first shot in a battle for
control of the Conservative party which Mr Major began planning during his
holiday in Portugal last month.
Mr Major's call for unity was backed by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor,
who dismissed as 'silly' and 'irrelevant' speculation that Mr Major faces a
leadership challenge in November.
Mr Clarke, regarded as the clear frontrunner in any battle for the
succession, poured scorn on the idea that he had been jostling for position
with Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, and Mr Michael Portillo, the
chief secretary to the Treasury. The chancellor said that Mr Major had the
unanimous backing of the cabinet and the firm support of the 'vast majority'
of Conservative MPs.
In typically robust form, Mr Clarke admitted on BBC Radio that the
government remained in the 'dreadful hole' he had first alluded to in early
summer. He warned again that he could not rule out further tax increases in
his November Budget.
Mr Clarke also refused to contemplate scrapping or scaling back the
government's intention to impose value added tax on domestic fuel despite a
weekend Mori opinion survey showing a backlash against the tax among party
activists. He said any change to the VAT plan would smack of 'weak
government'.
Mr Major offered an olive branch to his critics this morning in a speech
which dwelt on his vision for Europe - a main irritant in his battle with
the right.
Using language calculated to appeal to Euro-sceptic disciples of Lady
Thatcher, former prime minister, he said the European Community must 'take
account of the national identity, old cultures and proudly held traditions
of Europe's members'.
</TEXT>
