<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (20): Tiny twins turn
their attention to Europe - Profile, The Channel Islands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS RECENTLY as 30 years ago, the Channel Islands scarcely had an offshore
financial industry worthy of the name. Now, however, Jersey and Guernsey
together boast bank deposits of over Pounds 85bn and offshore investment
funds worth not far short of Pounds 30bn.
To put this into perspective, the two tiny islands - Jersey has a population
of rather more than 80,000, Guernsey of about 60,000 - have attained a size
statistically equivalent to between a fifth and a quarter of the banking and
investment funds industries on the UK mainland.
This is, of course, rather deceptive. These offshore centres are basically
booking and processing centres, and almost all of the money is actually sent
on to the UK or elsewhere for investment. And while Jersey and Guernsey are
big in these particular sectors, they are very small in life assurance and
pensions, because these kinds of investment lack the tax incentives that
have driven their growth on the mainland.
Guernsey and Jersey have also long been prominent in the area of offshore
trusts, a standard means by which wealthy people can hold assets out of
reach of mainland tax men. Another important service is offshore company
registration, sometimes for big multinational parent groups, but more
usually for family businesses or for the purpose of individual tax planning.
The relatively high costs of the Channel Islands mean that they find little
attraction in seeking low-value business from the mainland, although several
UK building societies market offshore deposit accounts from Jersey and
Guernsey. For a better choice of building societies, and a selection of
offshore life companies, try the Isle of Man, or Dublin.
In the past the staple business of Jersey and Guernsey has been providing
investment services to UK expatriates dotted around the world, who find it
convenient and safe to hold their investments in the tax-free Channel
Islands. More recently, however, the islands have been developing the
concept of 'offshore Europe', in order to attract custom from the European
Community, outside which they lie for the purposes of financial services.
Guernsey, in particular, has been forging interesting connections with
various Swiss banks which have found it less and less profitable to handle
private banking business within their own borders, mainly for tax reasons.
Geographically, the Channel Islands are reasonably well-positioned, within a
short plane ride of London, Paris, Zurich and other European centres, and in
this respect they score over centres such as Bermuda and Cayman. In terms of
type of business, they have positioned themselves in the middle of the
market, seeking business from the moderately wealthy - although the
super-rich probably still get a better service in Switzerland.
Quality of service can still be a problem. Labour shortages have been eased
by the recent recession, but investors who use offshore centres have to
balance the tax advantages with the frustrations and hassle of dealing with
faraway bank officials.
It is not easy to run substantial financial industries out there in amongst
the ocean waves, but Jersey and Guernsey manage the trick better than most
of their rivals.
</TEXT>
<XX>
