<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (16): A high-value premium
may cost less - Insuring your precious possessions / Specialist underwriters
know that anyone who can afford a home full of rare artefacts usually has
better security than the average householder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RICH art collectors living in big houses are generally a better risk for
insurance companies than the average householder, whose most valuable
possession may be a video recorder, yet this is not always reflected in
their respective insurance premiums.
'Most thieves would probably walk straight past a Rembrandt,' says Aron
Shapiro, of Artscope International, specialist fine art brokers. Young,
opportunistic burglars tend to go for easily disposable televisions and
videos, not unique works of art which are much harder to sell in a hurry.
Standard household insurance policies tend to be rated on the assumption
that your home is stuffed full of electrical goods and gold necklaces,
rather than old masters. The main risk that general insurers are concerned
with is theft, whereas for art or antiques, fire or water damage could be a
more serious threat. So collectors may be paying more than they need for
insurance, if they stick to standard policies.
Insurers who specialise in high-value home contents insurance can afford to
offer lower premiums, because claim rates are much lower than average.
Depending on the area, premiums for the high-value items can be as little as
a quarter of those with mainstream policies.
As a rule of thumb, if you are currently paying much more than Pounds 1,000
for household contents insurance, and you have a number of valuable
non-electrical items, it could be worth trying a specialist high-value
policy. Companies have different minimum premiums and sums assured, but if
you are on the borderline, insuring buildings and contents with the same
company could bring you into the net and cost you less overall.
The big names in the field are Hiscox, Nordstern and Sun Alliance, but a
broker should be able to help pick the most appropriate one for you. This
type of insurance is nearly always sold through brokers rather than direct,
as policies have to be tailored to individual requirements, demanding more
involvement from the broker than most off-the-peg household insurance.
Specialist underwriters have learned from experience that anyone who can
afford a home full of rare and beautiful artefacts usually cares enough
about them to have far better security than the average house.
Most proposal forms will ask detailed questions about locks and burglar
alarms, while some insurers insist on carrying out a security audit of your
home, and making recommendations about how to improve it, before accepting
the risk. The good insurers, however, realise that while no one can object
to proper locks, the joy of collecting is ruined if everything has to be
kept in a bank vault or safe.
One problem with collectables is that, unlike stereo equipment, they cannot
easily be valued and replaced once they have disappeared. A customer may
feel that no money can adequately compensate for the loss of his lovingly
built up collection of pre-war cigarette cards, but he will demand
compensation anyway, and the insurance company's business is to attach a
price-tag to the priceless.
However, getting valuations on which both insurer and insured agree can
sometimes be tricky, particularly if the collection is an unusual one. This
is where the insurers' specialist knowledge and contacts can be useful for
finding an authority on the most obscure objects.
Specialist policies often operate on an 'agreed value' basis, which means
that the insurer accepts a valuation for an item and will pay that amount if
a claim is made. This makes the claims procedure simpler, but valuations
must be reviewed periodically to take account of fluctuations in the market.
Apart from price, specialist insurance policies also have the advantage of
cover designed specially to meet collectors' needs. For example, most have
clauses based on the idea that the loss of, or damage to, one item of a pair
or set will reduce the value of the remaining items. Insurers will either
pay for the lost value, or accept the remaining items as salvage and pay for
total loss.
Masterpiece, from Sun Alliance, automatically covers new acquisitions up to
a certain proportion of the total sum insured - so even if your house went
up in flames the day after you had bought a new painting at auction, it
would be covered.
Insurers are also involved in promoting schemes to make it harder for
thieves to dispose of stolen art objects, and improving the chances of
recovery. One is the Art Loss Register, which in spite of its name will
record the loss of not just works of art but any unique or rare item, with a
minimum value of Pounds 1,000. The register is international, and
subscribers include most big insurance companies, dealers and auction
houses. The police are increasingly taking an interest.
Another useful enterprise along the same lines is Trace magazine, which
publishes photographs and descriptions of stolen items, to alert anyone who
may have bought or been offered one. Both these systems rely on owners
keeping photographs and precise descriptions of their belongings in a secure
place for use in case of theft.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
