<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (14): Be sure your Will is
correctly drawn - Inheritance tax planning / The government's budget deficit
may be be an ominous sign for people who want to pass some wealth on to the
next generation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY STILLERMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INHERITANCE TAX has been called a 'voluntary tax'. It is possible to give
away a large part of your wealth, and if you survive for seven years from
the date of the gift, no IHT will be payable.
Indeed, the rules have never been more generous, with some businesses and
farming land now fully exempt from inheritance tax.
However, the cloud on the horizon is the current budget deficit. The
government needs to raise money from somewhere, and while it is more likely
that the finance will be found from VAT, national insurance and income tax,
which are more widely based, it is quite possible that inheritance tax rates
could increase or the regime be changed so that it is less flexible.
The table shows that it is important to ensure that your will is
tax-efficient.
A husband and wife each have a nil band of Pounds 150,000. In the first
example, that band is not being used by the husband, so that Pounds 340,000
is payable to the Inland Revenue when the wealth passes to the children on
the second death. However, in the second example, both husband and wife
utilise their nil rate band on their respective deaths, thereby saving
Pounds 60,000 of tax.
If you examine the value of your estate, your house may be one of your
largest assets. It is also a non-income producing asset, so that, if it were
to be given away, your income would not fall. Unfortunately the
gift-with-reservation provisions do not allow you to merely give your house
to beneficiaries, such as your children, if you continue to live there while
they do not. If you do so and do not pay a market rent to your children,
then the provisions will still enable the Inland Revenue to tax the value of
your home as though it were part of your estate.
However, these provisions do not apply on death, so that if a husband and
wife were to hold their house as tenants in common, they could then give a
share of the house to their children, or in trust for their children, on the
first death. This is a useful way of using the nil rate band.
For example, if the house is worth Pounds 300,000, then a half share of the
house could be given to the children on the first death, with the surviving
spouse keeping the remaining 50 per cent share.
This does not give the surviving spouse security of tenure, as the children
could force a sale of the property; but if the family relationship is sound,
it may be a good way of using the nil rate band.
There are other methods of giving away a house while continuing to live
there using certain leasehold arrangements, but a great deal of care is
required in these more complex arrangements, which should only be considered
if the value of the home is very significant.
If you are the founder of your family business, the improvement in business
property relief discourages you from passing your shares to your children,
because, if those shares are increasing in value, your children would
acquire the shares at probate value for capital gains tax purposes on your
death. However, it is quite possible that business property relief at 100
per cent may not be available forever, so that you may wish to consider a
making a gift of shares now while there may be no charge to stamp duty,
capital gains tax or inheritance tax.
Many wealthy individuals are too concerned with the Pounds 3,000 IHT annual
exemption. Although they are correct in taking advantage of this tax
exemption, planning should not end here, as a larger gift only becomes
taxable if the donor dies within seven years; and after three years,
tapering relief applies so as to reduce the tax charge.
Also, if you have surplus income after tax and your normal living
expenditure, then this income can be given to your children without
inheritance tax being payable if properly structured.
The following illustrates the points:
                     Pounds 000
Taxable income               80
Tax (say)                   (26)
Annual expenditure          (40)
Regular annual gifts        (10)
Remaining surplus             4
There are other arrangements which are worth considering if you have left
planning very late. For elderly people, there are available plans that
enable you to continue to enjoy income, provide you with scope to receive
back your capital while also making a substantial gift now, which could
reduce the inheritance tax charge even if you die the day after making the
gift.
Barry Stillerman is a tax partner with Stoy Hayward, chartered accountants.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Husband     Wife      Children  Inland Revenue
                       Pounds 000  Pounds 000  Pounds 000    Pounds 000
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
FIRST EXAMPLE:
Current estate              1,000
Transfer on first death    (1,000)      1,000
Transfer on second death               (1,000)      1,000
IHT 150 at nil                                        nil           340
850 at 40 per cent                                   (340)
1,000                                                 660
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
SECOND EXAMPLE:
Current estate              1,000
Transfer on first death    (1,000)        850         150
Transfer on second death                 (850)        850
                                                    1,000
IHT 150 at nil                                        -
700 at 40 per cent                                   (280)          280
850                                                   720
Tax saving                                                           60
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
