<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (13): Rising markets will
pull more into the net - Capital gains tax planning / The Inland Revenue
expects increased turnover in stocks and property. Scheherazade Daneshkhu
considers some of the measures that can help to reduce the bill on gains
above the annual exemption
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAPITAL GAINS tax is not a problem for most people. The number who pay it
has been falling steadily. In the 1992-93 tax year, there were 1.6m
higher-rate taxpayers, but only 85,000 taxpayers faced a bill for CGT,
compared with 155,000 in 1989-90.
The amount of CGT assessed by the Inland Revenue has also been falling, from
Pounds 2.8bn in 1989-90 to Pounds 1.2bn in 1992-93.
The drop was influenced by the relatively poor performance of the stock
market. However, the Inland Revenue expects an increase in turnover in
stocks and property, and estimates that 125,000 taxpayers will be eligible
for CGT in the current tax year. An oddity introduced by the 1993 Finance
Act is that, in some cases, the existence of capital gains can produce an
extra income tax bill as well as a CGT bill.
CGT is charged on gains made when disposing of assets. You are allowed to
make Pounds 5,800 of gains in the current tax year before being liable to
CGT. Some assets, such as your main home, are exempt from CGT.
Measures which reduce the bill on gains above the annual exemption are an
indexation allowance, which gives protection from the effects of post-1982
inflation, and the ability to offset losses against gains.
One investment trust, launched this year by Ivory &amp; Sime, was based on
exploiting the annual CGT exemption. The Isis trust automatically sells 7
per cent each year of an investor's original capital in order to generate a
monthly income plan.
BES and Peps: The Business Expansion Scheme and Personal Equity Plans are
free of CGT. Investors can place Pounds 40,000 in a BES in a single tax year
but the investment must be held for five years for the CGT exemption to
apply. This is the last year of the BES which will be wound up on December
31.
There is no time limit on a Pep but the annual limits are relatively small.
Only a maximum of Pounds 9,000 (via a Pounds 6,000 general and a Pounds
3,000 single company Pep) can be invested in any one tax year.
The drawback with these investments is that if you were unlucky with them,
it would not be possible to offset losses against gains elsewhere.
Bed and Breakfasting: This is the term given to a sale one day and a
purchase the next of shares, to establish either a loss (to offset against
other gains) or to realise gains in order to use up as much as possible of
this year's allowance, since it cannot be carried forward.
The main problem with a bed-and-breakfast deal is that it involves costs,
such as commission and stamp duty, and it carries the risk that prices might
move while you are out of the market.
Bed and breakfasting does not work for 'relevant securities' - those covered
by the accrued-income scheme, deep-discount securities and shares in
non-qualifying offshore funds. Establishing an allowable loss on convertible
loan stock, for example, requires care, because the settlement day for the
re-acquisition must be later than that for the sale.
It is best to consult an accountant about CGT on the sale of non-listed
shares.
Married couples: If you are married (and living together), one way of
lessening the CGT bill in any single tax year is to transfer assets to your
spouse, in order to use his or her annual CGT exemption, or to ensure that
gains are taxed on the spouse with the lower tax rate. The transfer is
usually tax-free, and when the spouse comes to sell the asset it will be
taxed as if they had acquired it at the same price as you paid, broadly
speaking.
Deferring payment or sale of assets: Brian Todd, of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, says
that, if you are planning to leave the UK for more than one complete tax
year, you should defer the sale of any assets likely to incur a hefty CGT
liability, until after the end of the tax year in which you leave the
country. The assets can then be sold in the next tax year, and there will be
no CGT liability so long as the Inland Revenue regards you as not resident
(and not ordinarily resident) in the UK.
To minimise annual gains, Touche Ross suggests postponing disposals
scheduled for just before the end of the tax year until just after. This
reduces the gains taxable in the current year and delays the date on which
tax becomes payable. The danger is that tax rates may be higher in the next
year.
If you have no gains in one tax year but expect making them in the next,
Maurice Parry-Wingfield, of Touche Ross, suggests realising allowable losses
in the current tax year and carrying them forward to the next year. This
ensures that next year's gain is reduced by next year's annual exemption. If
the loss is realised next year, the gain will be reduced by the loss first,
so that the annual exemption would be wasted.
Full-time directors of unquoted companies, selling shares in their company,
can benefit from a new CGT relief. If they held at least 5 per cent of the
shares for at least one year and, in the last year, had invested (or planned
to invest within three years) in another unquoted company, they may be able
to hold over part of their gain and therefore defer the capital gains. Todd
says that the investor would have to hold at least 5 per cent of the shares
in the new company to qualify for the relief.
James Higgins, of fee-based advisers Chamberlain de Broe, recommends a
number of CGT planning devices for those with sizeable capital gains,
including the use of offshore bonds and 90/10 funds, which hold just under
90 per cent in sterling cash and 10 per cent in other currencies. These
funds can be used to establish an indexed book loss to offset against gains,
but are more effective in times of high inflation.
Higgins says that, in some cases, those with large share holdings in private
companies who wish to transfer assets to children or other members of the
family, may consider the use of a discretionary trust.
The transfer of shares into the trust is regarded as a disposal, and is
therefore liable to CGT. However, hold-over relief applies, whereby you are
effectively passing on the gain to the recipients. There is no capital gains
tax to pay on death, when your assets are instead liable to inheritance tax.
Since Pounds 150,000 of assets can currently be passed on to your heirs free
of inheritance tax, the discretionary trust is one way of getting around the
CGT problem for large shareholdings.
Relevant leaflets from the Inland Revenue are: CGT4 (owner occupied houses),
CGT 6 (retirement relief on disposal of a business), CGT13 (indexation
allowance for quoted shares), CGT 14 (an introduction), CGT15 (a guide for
married couples) and CGT16 (indexation allowance disposals after April 5
1988).
</TEXT>
