<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (11): Recovery due after a
year of problems - Tax-efficient investments 3, Enterprise zones / For the
investor who has a large sum to shield from tax, but has no great need of
income, here is a significant advantage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GREATEST relief from tax lies in enterprise zones. Once the Business
Expansion Scheme has disappeared, at the end of this year, they will offer
the only serious option for investors with significant sums to shelter from
tax.
However, that relief is only offered as a compensation for taking a serious
risk - investing in commercial property in depressed areas.
Promoters of enterprise zone investments have found that the route to
success, as with the BES, is to remove as much risk as possible.
They have succeeded to an extent. Some enterprise zone deals have been
secure, and have sold out quickly in consequence. But the market in
collective investments in enterprise zones has been damaged by a series of
embarrassments for promoters over the past two years, which have left
investors seriously out of pocket.
It is impossible to marginalise risk to the same extent as is achieved with
the BES. For that reason, it is best for most tax shelterers to take
advantage of the BES first, while it still exists, before moving on to
dabbling in enterprise zones.
The tax advantages are undeniable. As with the BES, you are entitled to
relief at your top marginal rate of tax, but without any upper limit, on
investments in enterprise zone property.
This gives EZs a significant advantage for the serious investor over the the
BES, which is limited to Pounds 40,000 a year.
Tax relief is available on loans taken out to fund the property, if the
interest is paid using rental income. And there is no fixed five-year
period.
Most serious investors, with large sums to shelter from tax, have no great
need of income, so this represents a significant advantage.
Special loan deals are often tied up in advance, and offered by enterprise
zone sponsors as an integral part of the investment.
Zone investment comes in two forms - either direct, or as part of enterprise
zone trusts. With a direct investment, you buy an enterprise zone property
outright. Unless you are buying only a small unit, this is likely to be
expensive.
Enterprise zone trusts (EZTs) are syndicated deals which buy a property, and
are then split into units for investment. This allows smaller investors to
invest in large buildings which might otherwise be beyond their scope.
It is also possible to buy into a spread of properties this way, hence
reducing risk. For these reasons, trusts have grown in popularity.
However, they have one big disadvantage compared with direct investment  -
the exit route. No EZT has yet been wound up and its profits realised, so
this remains completely untested. In most cases, it is possible for the
trust to sell after five years, if unitholders agree. Whether they will
agree, given the conflicts of interest which could emerge, and what price
they might receive, remain to be seen.
Some trusts have, in the past, offered defined exit routes by giving
developers options to buy at a fixed price after a fixed period.
How should you choose between trusts? According to Ian Pugh, of the
Allenbridge Group, the vital factor is a sizeable, secure income stream. If
you have this, then you can gear up to make the investment with some
confidence.
The yield (the rent paid each year expressed as a proportion of the purchase
price) is important here. Allenbridge avoided EZTs last year, because the
premium (in terms of a lower yield) which developers asked for in return for
EZ tax advantages was too great.
However, yields are now more in line with the market, according to Pugh,
allowing investors some genuine value.
Security is harder to legislate for. In an ideal situation, the property is
pre-let to a financially strong tenant. In a few cases, EZTs have even
bought property for government departments, whose covenants are obviously
very secure.
In other cases, covenants in force are much weaker. Bankers' guarantees
should be available as a fall-back on an EZT, to keep paying a fixed level
of rent if pre-arranged tenants default. These will only usually be
available for the first few years of the trust's existence, but add
significantly to the security.
EZTs with financially weak tenants, lacking the security of a bank
guarantee, are best avoided.
Last year, other problems also bedevilled EZ investors. A disagreement over
how the land element in a property purchase (which is not eligible for tax
relief) should be valued led to lengthy delays in tax relief being paid by
the Inland Revenue. Other schemes had to endure long waits before the
Revenue would confirm that they had qualified for tax relief.
These factors helped to make last year (1992-93) a disaster for the
industry, with only Pounds 43.2m invested in EZTs, compared with about
Pounds 160m in both of the two previous tax years. The popularity of BES
non-recourse loans did not help.
But next year, enterprise zone investment may well make a recovery. Once the
BES has disappeared, investors anxious to shelter from tax will have little
alternative.
But it is vital to examine the security and strength of the underlying
property. It never makes sense to make an investment for tax reasons alone.
</TEXT>
