<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / Fashion: A crash course in fashion on a grant - Sasha
Jensen, a third year at Warwick University, offers some tips for first-time
students on looking good on a tight budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SASHA JENSEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF YOU have won a place at university this October the words budget, budget
and budget will probably be echoing in your head. This is, after all,
probably the first time you will be officially in charge of your own life.
Apart from the precious pounds you will spend on books, accommodation and
food, there is the matter of your wardrobe. Clothes should be suitable for
the life you lead - and student life normally consists of going to and from
lectures, playing lots of sport and socialising in any and every pub you can
find. Thus you need to find some cheap but good-quality buys that will stand
you in good stead during your stay in academia.
The essentials are jumpers, jackets, track suits, tops, a decent pair of
shoes and some jeans - and you ought to be able to find all this for a
maximum of Pounds 100.
Marks and Spencer is an excellent first stop for the bargains essential to
every budget-conscious student. The M &amp; S unisex 'warmhandle' shirt (Pounds
29.95) is a thick, brushed cotton shirt which will keep the cold air away on
a wind-swept campus. It comes in red, black or a colourful Mexican-style
stripe. To match this there are jeans for men and women for Pounds 19.99
available in all colours.
Its lycra-jodhpurs (Pounds 19.99) are the basis of many a female student
wardrobe as they can be teamed with almost anything: the unisex M &amp; S
T-shirt (Pounds 7.99) or a round-neck ribbed top at Pounds 13.99 which comes
in black, white or lime. Look out also for a nice patterned wool/silk-mix
jumper (Pounds 35) in colours such as cream, lime and peach.
Young women heading straight for the disco after lectures should snap up the
M &amp; S crushed velvet, suede-look leggings - they are stunning in dark brown,
beige and black (Pounds 19.99) and would match the wool/silk jumper or the
arrow cuff and collar shirt (Pounds 19.99) which comes in white or blue.
The menswear department is always worth looking through - best buys I
spotted include striped rugby tops for Pounds 19.99 or a good black and red
checked shirt at Pounds 25.
To see you through three years you will need good quality shoes. For girls
there is the classic leather penny loafer in black or red-brown at a
reasonable Pounds 25.99, or the more dressy but less practical suede loafer
with a slight heel (Pounds 25). Boys could step out in M &amp; S's heavy
work-boots (Pounds 45), loafers in black and brown (Pounds 29.95) and a
reliable brogue at Pounds 29.95.
A really warm coat is vital. M &amp; S has two types of fleece jacket which will
shelter you from colds, flu and bankruptcy: a navy blue zip-jacket with
checked collar at a mere Pounds 35 or a blue and green check jacket which
zips at the front at the same price.
All students should make their way to a Levis store - a sturdy pair of jeans
is a must for college and Levis offers a 10 per cent discount to those who
can produce their library or student card. Levis has a new range of jeans
that might pass for casual trousers, which helps to explain the price. The
unisex 417 (Pounds 50) comes in saddle, blue, green, ecru and black. It has
a hugging fit but can be worn in a baggy style.
To match this there are short-sleeved, ribbed grandad tops in black, red,
white and cream at Pounds 20.70. The most interesting trouser design is the
Bedford cord (Pounds 50.50) which is close fitting and looks like a cross
between a cord and a jean.
Students who are really pushed for money should head for Flip in Long Acre,
Covent Garden, London. It is one of the cheapest places for T-shirts and
jeans, partly because most of the clothes it sells are second-hand. You can
find some second-hand Lee and Levis jeans for Pounds 15 downstairs. Upstairs
there is an array of second-hand jackets, waist coats and jeans going even
cheaper - from Pounds 10.
Flip sells new clothes, too: grandad tops for Pounds 16.99, T-shirts
starting at Pounds 4.99, long sleeved T-shirts at Pounds 9.99, track-suit
bottoms for Pounds 22.99 and a fluffy sweat-shirt top with a hood for Pounds
25.99.
Just two doors up from Flip is Longpoint Bay, where you can rummage around
for stylish bargains. The sweat jean-jacket Pounds 42.50 is shaped like the
classic jean-jacket, which means you can dress it up or down, with jeans or
trousers. If you are bored with the usual sweat-pants look Longpoint has its
own 'jogging trousers' which have a trouser-like effect because of the smart
zip that sits in the side of the leg. Colours for the jacket and joggers are
navy, bottle green, red, and grey.
To match these there are some long-sleeved button-up tops for the girls, in
grey and white (Pounds 22.99), and some button-up long-sleeved polo shirts
with ribbed cuff and collar in navy, red black, and bottle-green (Pounds
29.95). The unisex roll-neck polo top is a little number everyone could use
 -it can be worn with almost anything and is a sure way to keep warm in
student digs when winter arrives. Colours include mustard, crimson, cream,
black and navy. There is also an array of over-dyed jeans (Pounds 36.95) in
all sorts of colours, including blue, red, and green.
Another good port of call for budget shopping is the Next chain of stores.
The women's checked 'weekend' shirt at Pounds 29.99 is colourful and
thermal. The button-through V-neck jersey-top (Pounds 19.99 in black or
rose) can be worn either to the college disco or the daily seminar.
For boys there is a cotton striped rugby shirt in blues or red and green
(Pounds 29.99), or a heavy-knit polo-neck which comes in aqua and a light
cream. If anyone, male or female, wants a really cosy jumper then the
menswear section is the place to look. Next's ribbed neck and cuff sweater
(Pounds 34.99) is famous for its wonderful rib stitching. If you want a
heavier jumper then the chunky-rib turtle-neck fits the bill - it is
available in navy or stone for Pounds 29.99. Next also has some nice
sweat-shirts at Pounds 29.99 in blue and green.
Two other chains that women should look at are Oasis and River Island. The
Oasis Bohemian-print ankle-length skirt with lace-up top to match is an
outfit that is fashionable but flexible because it can be worn in the
evening or the day. There is a long white shirt which you can mix and match
with anything.
River Island has lots to offer the poundless student. There is a pinafore
dress with black and cream dot print (Pounds 39.99), a black button-through
flared skirt with white stitching (Pounds 16.99), some black lycra leggings
at (Pounds 9.99) and a grey, ribbed, cropped jersey top (Pounds 16.99).
Choose just a few of these items and you have yourself a wardrobe to take
you though winter, spring and summer - all for under Pounds 100.
</TEXT>
