<PROFILE>_AN-DISAKAD9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930918
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (7): An ill-fit for the
rich - Pensions, The earnings cap / The implications of the obstacle for
high-flyers' retirement aspirations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIVE YEARS ago, the government decided it would limit the subsidies it would
provide for the pensions of the truly wealthy.
Lord Lawson, in his memoirs, records the outcry over the so-called earnings
cap - second in volume perhaps only to that over the suggestion that
pensioners should no longer be allowed to take a portion of their retirement
benefits in a tax-free lump sum.
But the policy has remained, and increasing numbers of highly paid
individuals are having to seek alternative tax-beneficial ways to provide
additional income in their retirement.
The earnings cap was first set at Pounds 60,000 in 1989, meaning that an
employee could save enough money to entitle him to a pension of up to Pounds
40,000. After much debate, it was decided that the cap would rise annually,
but only in line with inflation as measured by the Retail Price Index.
Because national average earnings rise by 2 to 2.5 percentage points a year
faster than RPI, the industry calculated that, even those on relatively
modest earnings, could find themselves up against the earnings cap at some
point in the future. At that point they lose the tax advantages if they make
any further pension provision. High-flyers, who, through rapid promotion,
experience much larger pay rises, are likely to bump up against the cap even
more quickly.
Price Waterhouse estimates that a 40-year-old high-flying executive on the
relatively modest salary of Pounds 28,200 will bump up against the earnings
cap before reaching retirement age if his pay outstrips RPI by 4 percentage
points a year.
Things appeared even more ominous earlier this year, when the then
chancellor, Norman Lamont, citing the UK's low inflation rate, said the
earnings cap for the 1993-94 fiscal year would be frozen at Pounds 75,000,
and would not be allowed to rise to Pounds 77,400 as had been planned.
'This is the thin end of the wedge,' said Mr Ron Amy, chairman of the
National Association of Pension Funds and pension and benefits manager at
Grand Metropolitan. The NAPF fears that the move will provide a precedent
for future chancellors seeking to raise cash by taxing the well-off.
But for all the anxiety, relatively few people have been affected so far.
That is because the limit only applies to members of occupational schemes
set up after March 14, 1989 or those people who joined existing schemes
after June 1, 1989.
'The sort of people who have been affected are those who are high earners
and who were recruited by head hunters to responsible positions since 1989,'
said Geoffrey Calvert, tax consultant at Price Waterhouse. Employers who
wished to attract and retain such people have had to figure out how to make
a pensions promise that the individual will regard as iron-clad. 'The issue
for the employee is one of security. They will want a funded promise,' Mr
Calvert said.
Because contributions attract no tax relief, anyone whose employer makes one
on his behalf will be hit with a tax bill for 40 per cent of the sum. Rather
than ask employees to take such a hit, some employers have been relying on
unfunded promises - that is, promising to pay the pension out of current
income when it falls due at some future date.
Stewart Ritchie, director of pensions at Scottish Equitable, said that
high-flyers can sometimes have their pension needs addressed by making
modifications to the existing scheme. For instance, it is typical for
employees to accrue 1/60th of their final pension entitlement for each year
of employment. After 40 years of service, a full two-thirds pension is
earned.
But Inland Revenue limits allow schemes to grant as much as 1/30th of final
pension accrual in each year. 'An individual earning Pounds 150,000 will be
able to accrue as much pension entitlement each year in a 1/30th scheme as
an individual earning Pounds 75,000 in a 1/60th scheme,' Mr Ritchie says.
Thus, depending on how much previous pension benefit the high-flyer has
accrued, employers may be able to find tax relief for pension contributions
simply by setting up a new scheme with a faster annual accrual rate.
Alternatively, the scheme may establish a separate section which accrues
benefits more quickly.
But for those who cannot take advantage of such a device, or those who are
not satisfied with unfunded benefits, the pensions industry has been
perfecting Furbs - the Funded Unapproved Retirement Benefit Scheme. Unlike
unapproved company schemes, there are no limits on the level of pension
benefits or lump-sum payments that can be provided.
Furbs will never offer the tax advantages of pension arrangements before the
earnings cap was set in place. But it can mitigate some of the more onerous
tax consequences, while offering greater flexibility in the payment of
pension benefits. 'You can retire at 45 if you want to,' Mr Ritchie said.
According to Price Waterhouse, Furbs become attractive when contributions
are likely to exceed Pounds 100,000 in total over the first two to three
years of contributions.
Furbs work like this: the high-flyer earns tax relief on pension
contributions up to the ceiling under the earnings cap. The employer then
makes the additional necessary contributions, which would attract a tax
charge on the employee as a benefit-in-kind. But typically, the employer
will pay the high-flyer's tax charge, treating it as a normal business
expense for his own tax purposes. Furbs offer an additional advantage to
employers, because contributions do not attract the National Insurance
contribution, currently at 9.25 per cent of full pay. The NIC savings thus
offsets some of the employer's pension expense.
The funds are then usually invested in an onshore trust, which attracts tax
at the basic-rate of 25 per cent on capital gains and 20 per cent on
dividend income. Alternatively, funds may be invested in an offshore trust,
which attracts no tax in certain cases. However, Mr Ritchie warns that the
Inland Revenue may not allow the tax advantages of offshore investments to
remain forever if it perceives that they are being widely exploited.
 -------------------------------------------
When you may hit the cap before retirement
 -------------------------------------------
The figures in the table show the level of
current earnings above which an individual
at the relevant current age can expect his
or earnings, at age 65, to exceed the then
level of the earnings cap, under two
different economic assumptions.
