<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (4): Everything under one
roof - Private banking / The implications of high street banks' entry into a
hitherto exclusive sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPETITION IS entering the genteel world of private banking, a market
increasingly coveted by providers of financial services as a relatively
risk-free way of selling services and products lucratively.
The high street banks have begun to invade territory mainly at the expense
of the traditional private banks. In July, Adam &amp; Co, an Edinburgh-based
private bank, was taken over by Royal Bank of Scotland. Earlier this year,
Barclays launched a private banking arm in Mayfair, to cater to the
investment needs of those with Pounds 500,000 or more in liquid assets.
Lloyds' private banking arm, launched in 1985, adopted a different strategy
from other private banks by requiring a minimum of only Pounds 75,000 of
disposable assets from its customers.
'The attraction of private banking for UK banks such as Lloyds and Barclays
is that it is almost exclusively asset management,' said Peter Kinahan,
editor of Private Banker International, a newsletter published by Lafferty.
'It does not tie up capital, it is non-lending and is very profitable for
the banks which get it right.'
Coutts and Lloyds are the two largest players in the UK market. Coutts,
perhaps the best-known name in private banking because of its association
with the royal family, has Pounds 6bn of client funds under management,
while Lloyds has Pounds 4.1bn, according to Datamonitor. Barings, Hill
Samuel and Guinness Mahon merchant banks are the next largest players.
Private banking originally offered wealthy investors a safe deposit for
their funds, with the possibility of loans. Today, increased demand for
investment advice and fund management has broadened the range of services,
until they are similar to those offered by other institutions such as
merchant banks or stockbrokers that have private banking arms.
Services include discretionary portfolio management, money market accounts,
trust management, insurance, school fees planning and tax advice, though
each bank is likely to have its own definition of what a private banking
service should offer.
'Private banking is not a defined set of services,' said Ian Woodhouse,
private banking consultant with Price Waterhouse Management Consultants. 'It
is a personalised service oriented towards investment.'
The emphasis in all cases is on the customer-banker relationship. 'We will
handle anything relating to our customers' financial affairs including
buying them a vintage car,' said Michael Maslinski, head of business
development, at Coutts private bank, speaking of the Campbell's Office, the
integrated financial and banking service offered to very high net worth
individuals.
Flexibility is also a defining characteristic. The minimum level of assets
can range between Pounds 75,000 and Pounds 1m, depending on the bank, but
you could still be accepted with nothing like this amount if you are the son
or daughter of a valued customer.
The same flexibility extends to charges. Private banking's bread and butter
comes from fee-based services, such as investment advice and moving money
between countries. But what you pay depends on how frequently you use the
services and the size of your portfolio. Charges are usually negotiable if
your portfolio is large.
'In the past, customers would not question the fees, but now prices tend to
be broken down so that you know how much you are paying for individual
services,' said Woodhouse. 'Whereas there used to be a fee for the overall
service, the tendency now is to make a charge for the service used.'
You may, however, be paying over the odds for personalised service. For
example, at Coutts, the basic banking service comes free only if you
maintain an average minimum of Pounds 3,000 in your account, otherwise there
is a quarterly charge of Pounds 30.
However, James Cooper, chief executive of Lloyds private banking, argues
that it can be cheaper to have all your financial needs managed in one
place. 'We charge a fee of 1 per cent for assets under management; you might
find yourself paying more by going to a series of advisers or fund
managers.' He says another advantage is that the charge for financial advice
can often be rolled into the fund mangement fees.
Assuming you have sufficient assets, why go to a private bank rather than an
investment house, stockbroker or a series of specialists, such as a
financial adviser and an accountant?
Cooper argues that the great attraction is the ability to have your banking
and other financial needs, including tax affairs, administered through the
private banking executive appointed for each customer. Other advantages are
enhanced banking facilities: the Lloyds service offers an automatic
borrowing facility of Pounds 17,500 at preferential rates of interest, as
well as a Pounds 500 daily cashpoint limit and a cheque guarantee card for
Pounds 250.
Woodhouse says that the form of assets you hold determines to a large extent
the type of bank you need. 'If your assets are mainly liquid, on deposits or
in bonds, there are banks which specialise in this. If your assets are
predominantly in securities, you'll look for a securities-oriented
institution with a global network. But if your assets are mainly in
property, you might choose a property/tax adviser.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
