<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (5): Expatriates can roll
it up offshore
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS WHO wish to keep their assets on deposit, but who are expatriates
or intend to move abroad, might consider offshore funds as an alternative to
holding money in a UK-based bank or building society, writes Scheherazade
Daneshkhu.
Many are similar to unit trusts; but, unlike their onshore counterparts,
offshore funds can pay income gross (though November's Budget may bring
change).
Offshore funds are broadly divided into two main types for UK tax purposes:
distributor and accumulator funds. Distributors must pay out 85 per cent of
their income as dividends. UK investors pay income tax on the dividends, but
any other profits are taxed as capital gains.
Accumulators do not pay out income, but 'roll it up' within the fund. Gains
are taxed as income, not capital gains, but only when investors sell their
holding. Accumulator funds can, therefore, be useful for postponing a tax
liability. If an investor knew he was going to retire and move into a lower
tax bracket, he could invest in a roll-up and take profits at the most
tax-efficient moment.
Furthermore, the roll-up can enhance performance. Since tax is postponed,
investors can compound their investment gross rather than net. Roll-up funds
tend to invest in the money markets, or in bonds, where income is high
enough to get the full benefit of the roll-up process.
Many investment houses offer a range of funds, allowing investors to switch
easily between cash, bonds and equities without incurring the same costs as
moving between different institutions. Investors can also switch between
currencies.
Investment for expatriates - see page 22
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6726 Investment Offices, NEC.
    P6282 Investment Advice.
    P6799 Investors, NEC.
</IN>
