<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (2): First, understand the
three varieties - Choosing a stockbroker / The decision is more of an art
than a science, says Philip Coggan. It's difficult, but a useful guide may
by provided by the performance of any unit or investment trusts that your
prospective broker runs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR SOME people with 'old money', the family stockbroker is like the doctor
and solicitor, a faithful adviser whose wisdom is passed from generation to
generation.
But those who have acquired their wealth more recently face the problem of
finding a broker for the first time. There is perhaps a natural suspicion
that the wrong choice may result in the loss of a hard-earned fortune - that
the quickest way of becoming a millionaire is to give a stockbroker Pounds
2m to invest.
The first step in choosing a broker is to understand that there are three
types of stockbroker:
Execution-only
Execution-only brokers will buy and sell shares on your behalf, without
giving any advice.
Their chief attraction is that their commissions are lower than those
charged by other brokers. Rivals sometimes claim that execution-only brokers
fail to get the best price in the market for their customers, and that this
negates the commission saving - but this argument is hotly disputed by the
execution-only sector.
Advisory
Advisory brokers, as their name suggests, will give clients advice on which
shares to buy, and at what price. However, the overall responsibility for
decisions remains with the client. The brokers receive their payment in the
form of commission every time the client deals.
Discretionary
Discretionary brokers take full charge of the client's portfolio. They may
charge a fee for this - based on a percentage of the amount of money managed
 -or they may earn their return in the form of commissions.
In recent years, there has been a tendency for advisory brokers to get
squeezed out by the other two types. Charging a fee to manage a portfolio
creates a stable source of income for the discretionary broker; cut-price
dealing services attract a mass market (and high volumes) for the
execution-only broker.
The advisory broker must rely on clients who may only decide to deal once or
twice a year. But the differences between the three categories are becoming
increasingly blurred.
Sharelink, for example, is an execution-only broker but it produces low-cost
information packs on companies, designed to help investors to pick shares.
Choosing a broker is rather more an art than a science. If one opts for an
execution-only service, it is slightly easier, since it is mainly a question
of opting for the lowest commission rate. (Nevertheless, wealthy investors
should take care. Some execution-only brokers slant their rates towards the
smaller investor).
Judging an advisory broker is also difficult, because it is virtually
impossible to quantify the value of advice. And even discretionary brokers
are hard to judge, because they will rarely be able to produce figures for
the 'average' client, on the grounds that each client has different needs
and a different level of tolerance for risk.
One useful guide can be provided by any unit and investment trusts run by
the broker. They have a published record, which can be checked in
publications such as the FT's sister magazine, Money Management. If the unit
and investment trusts have not performed well in their sectors, that ought
to say something about the firm's investment management skills.
But qualitative, rather than quantitative, measures may be important. You
may well wish to be able to speak regularly to a named broker; you may want
the firm to handle all your dividend payments and associated tax credits,
and to deal with your capital gains tax planning. You should certainly
expect regular, and easy-to-understand, portfolio valuations.
Where might you expect investments to be made? Mercury Asset Management
describes a typical portfolio, for a UK client, as: UK shares, 60 per cent;
cash/bonds, 17 per cent; European shares, 8 per cent; US shares, 7 per cent;
Far Eastern shares, 4 per cent; and Japanese shares, 4 per cent.
Some brokers offer money market accounts, which pay competitive rates of
interest on cash held by clients as they move between equity investments.
And services can be a lot more sophisticated than that.
Prudential Bache Securities, for example, has a Luxembourg-based private
bank, which will lend customers money against the value of their stock
portfolios.
A good broker ought to have no problems in buying and selling overseas
shares, or indeed in offering services in other major currencies such as the
US dollar.
Nor do you need to rely on the investment skills of one broker alone.
Pru-Bache also offers Managed Assets Consulting Services which gives
investors the choice of a range of top money managers, whose services might
not be otherwise available for individuals.
A similar concept is provided by the Optima fund, a Bermuda-registered fund
run by Dixon Boardman, formerly of Kidder Peabody, which selects the 12 best
managers of US mutual funds. The minimum investment is Dollars 500,000.
For some, all these additional services may be irrelevant; all they want is
a broker that they can rely on to be careful with their money. The
recommendation of a friend or colleague may well be the best guide.
But for those who want to find their own broker, a list can be obtained from
the Association of Private Client Managers and Stockbrokers, 5th floor, 20
Dysart Street, London EC2A 2BX.
