<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / FT Guide For The Serious Investor (1): Life without
double-digit returns - Introduction / As investors face a period of
adjustment, they should realise that tax-saving is not everything
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FINANCIAL services industry is eager to befriend the wealthy investor.
Whether your lump sum comes from a redundancy pay-off, an early retirement
package, the sale of a business, or the death of a relative, you will be
sure to find plenty of people willing to advise you how to invest it.
The problem lies in telling the difference between those who will make you
wealthier still and those who will make themselves wealthy at your expense.
Those who seek to help will display themselves in many guises:
private-client stockbrokers, private bankers, independent financial
advisers, financial planners, solicitors and accountants. Often the services
will be very similar: private client stockbrokers offer money market
accounts for your spare cash; private bankers emphasise their skills in
money management.
Choosing an adviser may, in the end, come down to whether you feel you can
trust the individual concerned, whatever the category of organisation he or
she works for. A good rule of thumb is to distinguish between technical and
investment expertise. There are plenty of people who can give sound advice
about tax and pension planning. But it would be a mistake to assume that
your accountant knows where the stock market will be in six months time, or
whether ICI will outperform Hanson. If he knew all the investment answers,
he would have quit accountancy to live in Barbados long ago.
Many investors will feel the need for a good adviser at the moment. For
those who live off the income from their savings, the past three years have
been challenging. Interest rates have tumbled around the world, reducing the
attraction of the easy option of keeping money on deposit.
Those who managed to switch out of cash at the right time - UK long gilt
yields were still 12 per cent in early 1990 - have reaped the benefits. But
many people realised what was happening late in the day and have only
started to contemplate the switch in recent months.
For them, choices are difficult. Lower interest rates have led to a rally in
the prices of financial instruments. Bond yields have tumbled - 30-year US
Treasuries were offering a touch over 6 per cent in August, long gilt yields
around 7.5 per cent. Meanwhile, equity yields dropped below 3 per cent in
the US, and 4 per cent in the UK. Even though economic recovery appears to
be under way in both countries, those yield valuations look quite expensive
by historical standards.
So not only do equities and bonds offer, by recent standards, a modest
income; there is always the prospect that if the interest-rate cycle turns,
there may be a sharp fall in share and bond prices.
Nevertheless, with inflation subdued in most leading economies, the world
could be due for a long period of low interest rates. The bulls argue that
the old measures of equity valuations, based on periods when inflation was
much higher, are no longer relevant.
Even so, investors face a severe psychological adjustment: they can no
longer expect the double-digit percentage returns they received in the past.
Some argue that a major investment theme of the moment is the gradual
transfer of economic power from the high-wage west to the low-wage
developing world, and in particular the Far East. The correct investment
approach, therefore, is to buy bonds in the developed world and equities in
the so-called emerging markets. Certainly, a week rarely passes at the
moment without a new emerging markets fund being launched on an enthusiastic
investment community.
For those seeking ideas for their own investment strategies, this survey
includes articles on portfolio planning - with tips from three financial
advisers - and on unit and investment trusts, which the wealthy can easily
overlook.
Tax is also a very important issue for the wealthy investor, especially as
the 1980s tax-cutting tide appears to be receding, with governments in the
US, UK and Germany all producing tax-raising packages.
For the British investor, there are a number of tax breaks available, from
the soon-to-be-abolished Business Expansion Scheme (BES) to the flourishing
personal equity plan (Pep). The survey has articles on the major shelters,
as well as pieces on coping with capital gains tax and inheritance tax, and
on setting up a family trust.
As a wise investor once said, 'there are worse things in life than paying
taxes', and it is a mistake to be carried away by the tax-free label. It is
far better to earn 10 per cent and pay tax on the profits than to lose 5 per
cent in some badly timed tax-free investment.
Nevertheless, sometimes the tax shelters seem too good to be true; under the
BES, for example, cash-backed property deals can offer to double the
top-rate taxpayer's money over five years at minimal risk. And Peps have
probably been of most benefit to wealthy investors (the most likely to pay
CGT), who have simply transferred a chunk of their portfolios into tax-free
form.
For the international investor, it is the offshore tax havens that supply
the siren voice. It is a mistake to think these havens are really tax-free:
a UK investor is obliged to pay tax on his or her worldwide income. But a
classic use for an offshore fund is to postpone tax until the individual is
in a lower, or simply more advantageous, tax bracket.
The activities of Bernie Cornfeld, and more recently Barlow Clowes, have
indicated the dangers of investing beyond the regulators' net. Some offshore
centres, concerned about their reputations, have tightened up their
regulations and established compensation schemes; in the Managed Funds pages
of the FT, investors should look for the label 'SIB-recognised', which
indicates regulation of a standard similar to that applying in the UK.
Such is the potential of the 'jet-set' market that many highly respectable
firms have set up offshore funds. The giant US group Fidelity, for example,
has a range of money market funds in Bermuda and a range of equity and bond
funds in Luxembourg.
With modern executives frequently moving between countries, the offshore
market is likely to grow substantially; so this survey contains an article
on financial planning for expatriates and a profile of the Channel Islands.
Finally, the serious investor should not forget the importance of other
types of cover; which is why the survey has pieces on insurance, both for
your life and for your possessions, and, given the ever-rising cost of
healthcare, on the latest medical insurance plans. Failure to insure oneself
properly against these costs may be more financially ruinous than making the
wrong stock-picking decision.
</TEXT>
