<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / Birt pledges extra Pounds 75m savings in next two years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Birt, director-general of the BBC, yesterday said that in the next
two years the corporation would save an extra Pounds 75m which would be put
into programmes.
The savings - Pounds 50m next year and Pounds 25m the year after - will
follow the Pounds 100m savings expected in the current financial year. They
come largely from reduced BBC bureaucracy and from the introduction of
Producer Choice, the controversial system which allows producers to buy
services from the outside market.
Mr Birt told the Royal Television Society's Cambridge convention: 'It is
ludicrous to present it (Producer Choice) as a shambles.'
He was speaking the day after Mr Peter Brooke, national heritage secretary,
praised the BBC governors and management for improvements in the corporation
and the courage shown in tackling difficult issues.
Mr Brooke warned, however: 'If the BBC had not made, and does not continue
to make changes, the future of the licence fee in the short term and of the
BBC itself in the longer term might need to be considered from a very
different perspective.'
The statement was seen as tacit government support for the reforms
introduced by Mr Birt.
A government white paper on the renewal of the BBC's Royal Charter is due in
the next six months. The principle of the BBC licence fee is not expected to
be in doubt, but proposals for change could include the privatisation of the
BBC transmitter network.
Mr Alan Yentob, BBC 1 controller, yesterday accepted suggestions that
ideally he needed an additional Pounds 50m to Pounds 100m for programme
scheduling. BBC 1 is to receive Pounds 60m from the planned Pounds 100m
savings.
Mr Yentob accepted that this summer's level of repeats had probably been too
high. Repeats on BBC television are running at about 20 per cent during
prime time.
The BBC is to cut up to 131 jobs through a merger in research and
development, it said yesterday. The savings of more than Pounds 5m will go
to programme-making.
The corporation said that some redundancies would be achieved by not
renewing contracts, but that there may be compulsory job losses.
The plan to merge engineering research and development, currently run as two
separate departments with 281 staff, will take effect from April 1 next
year.
</TEXT>
