<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / ICI to end free hamper scheme
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ICI ON Teesside is to stop giving free Christmas hampers to its pensioners
in order to save money as it continues its restructuring.
Since hamper distribution began 25 years ago, the number of people
qualifying has grown more than fifteenfold to well over 15,000, and now
threatens to be twice the number of ICI staff in the area.
The cost of issuing the hampers now exceeds Pounds 200,000 a year - a sum
described by ICI as prohibitive.
The news that this year's Christmas hamper will be the last broke in a
letter to the pensioners from Mr David Allan, ICI on Teesside's personnel
manager.
The TGWU general union deplored the move, but ICI said some pensioners had
said they understood the decision.
