<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / Vodafone tariff cuts intensify price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VODAFONE, the UK's leading cellular mobile operator, has cut its London and
low-user tariffs to match those offered by Cellnet - intensifying the price
war in the industry.
The low-user tariff drops by 15 per cent, and a reduced-rate tariff comes in
for the London region, giving business users a 20 per cent price cut for
calls made in the London region in return for higher prices for calls made
outside.
The cuts are virtually identical to those announced by Cellnet a fortnight
ago, and reflect growing competition in the industry.
Competition was given a significant boost last week with the launch of the
Mercury One-2-One network within the M25 area. The new service features free
evening calls at week-ends for personal subscribers.
Vodafone's new London tariff - 'CapitalCall' - comprises a monthly
subscription of Pounds 20, with call charges of 20p a minute peak-rate
inside the M25 and 50p a minute outside.
Vodafone has also introduced special incentives for users with bills of more
than Pounds 62.50 a month.
</TEXT>
