<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 93 / Bosnia peace on Tuesday, says Owen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD OWEN, the international mediator, yesterday gave his strongest
indication to date that a peace agreement could be close in Bosnia, when he
said he expected the three warring sides to sign a deal when they meet in
Sarajevo on Tuesday.
Speaking in Macedonia on an intense round of diplomatic lobbying, Lord Owen
said: 'I expect that the agreement will be signed on Tuesday. It will be a
very difficult agreement, but it must be signed.'
The accord that the three sides have been asked to 'consider signing' on
Tuesday proposes a loose 'union' of three ethnic mini-states, with
provisions for the states to secede at a later date.
With many of the territorial issues still apparently unresolved, the tactics
of the mediators now appear to be to press for an outline peace settlement,
hoping that the final boundary details can be worked out at a later date.
But, as an indicator of the problems that will dog any deal, Mr Alija
Izetbegovic, Bosnian president, reiterated that he will not sign a deal
without further territorial concessions.
The latest round of peace talks broke down three weeks ago, when Serb and
Croat leaders refused the Bosnian government's demand for an extra 4 per
cent of territory, on top of the 28 per cent which the agreement now offers
them.
Although the commanders of the Moslem and Croat forces in Bosnia yesterday
agreed to a ceasefire, due to take effect at 10 am GMT today, fierce
fighting between Moslem and Croat forces was reported to be continuing in
central Bosnia, around the cities of Mostar and Vitez.
By way of a separate blow to the peace process, Serb forces were also
reported to have shelled Knin, in the Serb-controlled Krajina enclave, in
Croatia.
</TEXT>
