FT  17 SEP 93 / International Company News: Portugal's Marconi up 11% after
six months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANHIA Portuguesa Radio Marconi, the Portuguese government-controlled
telecoms group, yesterday reported net profits for the first half of 1993 of
Esc2bn (Dollars 12.2m), an 11 per cent increase compared with the same
period last year.
Operating profits grew by 14 per cent to Esc3.7bn and cash flow increased by
12 per cent to Esc4.5bn.
Mr Goncalo Sequeira Braga, Marconi's president, said the results showed a
strengthening in the company's financial structure in terms of solidity,
autonomy and solvency.
He also reported a significant reduction in indebtedness and an important
increase in capital to Esc43bn, compared with Esc37bn the previous year.
Portugal's telecoms sector is undergoing an important restructuring, with
two wholly state-owned companies and Marconi, which is 49 per cent
privately-owned, being brought together under a single government-controlled
holding company, Comunicacoes Nacionais.
Marconi has a licence to operate intercontinental calls to and from
Portugal, but is also bidding for a concession to operate inter-European
services.
The company forecasts that net profits will exceed Esc4bn for all of 1993,
an increase of 15 per cent on 1992.
